.TH _PRINTF 3 "April 2026" "Holberton School" "Library Functions Manual"
.SH NAME
_printf \- custom formatted output conversion
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B #include "main.h"
.PP
.BI "int _printf(const char *" format ", ...);"
.SH DESCRIPTION
The
.B _printf()
function produces output according to a
.I format
string and writes it to stdout.
.PP
The
.I format
string is composed of zero or more directives: ordinary characters
(not
.BR % ),
which are copied unchanged to stdout, and conversion specifications,
each of which results in fetching zero or more subsequent arguments.
.SS Conversion specifiers
.TP
.B %c
Prints a single character.
.TP
.B %s
Prints a string of characters. If the argument is NULL, prints (null).
.TP
.B %d
Prints a signed decimal integer.
.TP
.B %i
Prints a signed decimal integer.
.TP
.B %%
Prints a literal percent sign. No argument is consumed.
.SH RETURN VALUE
.B _printf()
returns the number of characters printed (excluding the null byte
used to end output to strings).
Returns \-1 if
.I format
is NULL.
.SH EXAMPLES
Print a simple string:
.PP
.RS
.nf
_printf("Hello, World!\en");
.fi
.RE
.PP
Print an integer:
.PP
.RS
.nf
_printf("Number: %d\en", 42);
.fi
.RE
.PP
Print a character and string:
.PP
.RS
.nf
_printf("%c is for %s\en", 'C', "coding");
.fi
.RE
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR printf (3),
.BR write (2),
.BR stdarg (3)
